%T A395321 0,0,8,7,9,8,8,7,9,5,0,1,2,0,8,2,3,8,6,9,2,6,6,6,0,4,8,6,5,2,6,8,7,6,
%U A395321 9,0,6,5,2,9,3,2,6,2,5,9,5,6,8,3,9,4,9,5,3
%N A395321 Decimal expansion of the conjecturally maximum possible volume of a polyhedron with 16 vertices inscribed in the unit sphere.
%C A395321 Due to the high symmetry of the arrangement of the vertices (tetrahedral symmetry group S_4 with order 24), there is hope that an analytical representation of this constant exists, but this is not yet known.
%C A395321 From _Natalia L. Skirrow_, Jun 04 2026: (Start)
%C A395321 The polyhedron can be written with vertex coordinates:
%C A395321 ( t, t, t),
%C A395321 ( t,-t,-t) (3 perms),
%C A395321 ( r,-s, s) (6 perms),
%C A395321 (-r, s, s) (3 perms),
%C A395321 (-r,-s,-s) (3 perms),
%C A395321 (closed under the symmetry operations "permute axes" and "flip two signs"), with t=1/sqrt(3), and r^2+2*s^2 = 1. Decimal expansions:
%C A395321 t = 0.57735026918962576450914878050196,
%C A395321 r = 0.91157938253114920597802631908894,
%C A395321 s = 0.29070864223834896670682754080185.
%C A395321 The polyhedron is constructible out of radial tetrahedra, in particular (the equivalence classes up to S_4 of):
%C A395321 I = {(0,0,0),(t,t,t),(r,-s,s),(r,s,-s)} (12 representatives),
%C A395321 J = {(0,0,0),(t,t,t),(s,-v,r),(r,-s,s)} (12 reps),
%C A395321 E = {(0,0,0),(-s,-s,-r),(-s,-r,-s),(-r,-s,-s)} (4 reps).
%C A395321 These have volumes:
%C A395321 vol(I) = det([[t,t,t],[r,-s,s],[r, s,-s]])/6 = 2*t*r*s/3,
%C A395321 vol(J) = det([[t,t,t],[s,-s,r],[r,-s, s]])/6 = t*(r-s)*(r+3*s)/6,
%C A395321 vol(E) = det([[r,s,s],[s, r,s],[s, s, r]])/6 = (r-s)^2*(r+2*s)/6,
%C A395321 so the total polyhedron's volume is V(r) = (8*r*s + 2*(r-s)*(r+3*s))*t + 2*(r-s)^2*(r+2*s)/3, where s is defined implicitly.
%C A395321 V'(r) = (10*r)*t + 5*r^2 + 8*s/t - 2*r*s - 2/(s*t) - 1, which Mathematica's Solve reduces to the minpoly:
%C A395321 69 - 73*sqrt(3)*r - 130*r^2 + 82*sqrt(3)*r^3 +  25*r^4 + 27*sqrt(3)*r^5 = 0; the other way around,
%C A395321  9 -  3*sqrt(3)*s -  94*s^2 -  6*sqrt(3)*s^3 + 113*s^4 - 27*sqrt(3)*s^5 = 0.
%C A395321 The polyhedron's volume has the minimal polynomial:
%C A395321 3784084398958182400 - 1457973565222551552*V^2 + 179253470562877440*V^4 - 7618104759214080*V^6 + 74727572486976*V^8 - 847288609443*V^10 = 0,
%C A395321 or where W = V^2*3^2/2^5,
%C A395321 3695394920857600 - 632801026572288*W + 34578215772160*W^2 - 653129694720*W^3 + 2847415504*W^4 - 14348907*W^5 = 0.
%C A395321 The field extensions over Q formed by the minpolies of r/sqrt(3), s/sqrt(3) and W all have Galois group S_5, so none have a closed form in terms of radicals.
%C A395321 (End)
%H A395321 Hugo Pfoertner, <a href="https://www.randomwalk.de/sphere/volmax/pages/16.htm">Visualization of Polyhedron</a>, (1999).
%H A395321 Hugo Pfoertner, <a href="https://www.randomwalk.de/sphere/volmax/videos/16c.mp4">Number of edges incident with the 16 vertices</a>, video (2021).
%H A395321 Polytope Wiki, <a href="https://polytope.miraheze.org/wiki/Hexakis_truncated_tetrahedron">Hexakis truncated tetrahedron</a>.
%e A395321 2.886455392274518582747381678285489...
%o A395321 (PARI) my(s3=sqrt(3), t=1/s3, s=vecmax(polrootsreal(9 - 3*s3*s - 94*s^2 - 6*s3*s^3 + 113*s^4 - 27*s3*s^5)), r=vecmax(polrootsreal(69 - 73*s3*r - 130*r^2 + 82*s3*r^3 +  25*r^4 + 27*s3*r^5))); (8*r*s + 2*(r-s)*(r+3*s))*t + 2*(r-s)^2*(r+2*s)/3 \\ _Hugo Pfoertner_, Jun 05 2026
